XV. With jurisdiction is connected the immunity which the Roman ecclesiastics errogate to themselves. For they consider it a degradation for them to appear before a civil judge in personal causes, and they imagine the liberty and dignity os the Chnrch to consist in their exemption from the common judicature and laws. But the ancient bishops, who in other respects were the most rigid assertors of the rights of the Ghurch, esteemed it no injury to themselves, orto their order, to be subject to lay judges in civil causes. The pious empe- rors also, without any opposition, always summoned the clergy before their tribunals, whenever necessity required it. For this is the language of Constantine, in his epistle to the bishops os Nicomedia: “ ls any bishop excite any disturbance by his, indiscretion, his presumption shall be restrained hythe author· ity of the minister os God, that is, by mine.” And Valentinian says, “ Good bishops never traduce the power of the emperor, but sincerely observe the commands of God, the sovereign King, and obey our laws.'’ At that time this principle was universally admitted, without any controversy.
